## 6. Amino acid residue properties (for protein change wording)

Use when describing amino acid changes (e.g. “replaces X, which is neutral and non-polar, with Y, which is acidic and polar”). All 20 standard amino acids in proteins; properties refer to the **side chain (R group)** at physiological pH. *Sources: biochemistry texts, [NYU Proteomics](https://education.med.nyu.edu/mbm/proteomics/properties.shtml), [Chem LibreTexts](https://chem.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Introductory_Chemistry/The_Basics_of_General_Organic_and_Biological_Chemistry_(Ball_et_al.)/18:_Amino_Acids_Proteins_and_Enzymes/18.01:_Properties_of_Amino_Acids).*

**Charge / polarity (side chain):**
- **Acidic (negatively charged):** Asp (D), Glu (E) — side chain has carboxylate (COO⁻).
- **Basic (positively charged):** Lys (K), Arg (R), His (H) — side chain carries positive charge at pH 7.
- **Polar uncharged (hydrophilic):** Ser (S), Thr (T), Asn (N), Gln (Q), Tyr (Y), Cys (C) — can H-bond; not charged.
- **Nonpolar / hydrophobic:** Ala (A), Val (V), Leu (L), Ile (I), Phe (F), Trp (W), Met (M), Pro (P), Gly (G) — do not have charged or strongly polar side chains.

**Quick lookup (3-letter → property for wording):**

| 3-letter | 1-letter | Property (for “which is …”) |
|----------|----------|-----------------------------|
| Ala | A | nonpolar, hydrophobic |
| Arg | R | basic, positively charged |
| Asn | N | polar uncharged (amide) |
| Asp | D | acidic, negatively charged |
| Cys | C | polar uncharged (thiol, can form disulfide) |
| Gln | Q | polar uncharged (amide) |
| Glu | E | acidic, negatively charged |
| Gly | G | small, neutral (no side chain) |
| His | H | basic, positively charged (imidazole) |
| Ile | I | nonpolar, hydrophobic |
| Leu | L | nonpolar, hydrophobic |
| Lys | K | basic, positively charged |
| Met | M | nonpolar, hydrophobic (sulfur) |
| Phe | F | nonpolar, hydrophobic (aromatic) |
| Pro | P | nonpolar, cyclic (rigid) |
| Ser | S | polar uncharged (hydroxyl) |
| Thr | T | polar uncharged (hydroxyl) |
| Trp | W | nonpolar, hydrophobic (aromatic) |
| Tyr | Y | polar uncharged (aromatic hydroxyl) |
| Val | V | nonpolar, hydrophobic |

**Example wording:** “This variant (p.Gly1098Asp) replaces **glycine**, which is **neutral and non-polar**, with **aspartic acid**, which is **acidic and polar**, at the 1098th amino acid position.”

Use this knowledge when explaining variants, writing filters, or designing AutoVariant logic.
